question.en-US: Will you sell the works in your collection?

answer.en-US: Salon is building an institutional collection, holding our works for decades to come. Our organization is set up to exist in perpetuity, not to “flip” or sell artworks for gains.

question.en-US: What is decentralization?

answer.en-US: Decentralization means that Salon has no leader or owner—all of the works in our collection are shared amongst our community. We pool our funds, knowledge, and access, relying on our hive mind and a democratic voting process to form consensus on acquisition decisions.

question.en-US: How do you decide who gets to take what home?

answer.en-US: After an acquisition is made, the member who originally proposed the work is given first priority as host. If they decline, the order in which members joined Salon governs who can take it home. We repeat this process until all members have one, two, three works…and so on.

question.en-US: What is Salon?

answer.en-US: Salon is a member-managed contemporary art collection, owned and operated by a global community of collectors, artists, and gallerists. Our Internet-based institution is building the world’s largest co-owned art collection, with works on display throughout the homes of our members around the world.

question.en-US: Where are the artworks in Salon’s collection held?

answer.en-US: Our members host works from our collection in their homes, where they can be cherished by friends and family alongside works in our personal collections.

question.en-US: How is Salon structured?

answer.en-US: Salon is structured as a Delaware limited liability company (LLC). Our operating agreement expressly limits our members' liability and limits any fiduciary obligations amongst members.

question.en-US: Are Salon units tokens or cryptocurrency?

answer.en-US: No. Salon units are not tokens or cryptocurrency, are not stored in your digital wallet, and are not tradable on any public secondary market. Our units are held within our app’s ledger system, are associated with your digital wallet, and are used primarily for internal operations, voting, and calculating pro rata ownership.

question.en-US: What are the tax obligations for members of Salon?

answer.en-US: Salon is treated as a pass-through partnership for US income tax purposes, where income is passed through to members to report on their individual tax returns. Like a typical fund or investment vehicle, Salon prepares annual K-1s for all members, and members file taxes for any realized gains annually.

question.en-US: How do you transfer funds into Salon?

answer.en-US: Investors can contribute capital by bank wire or by using a MetaMask digital wallet. Members can contribute to Salon only after they have been verified as an accredited investor and approved to join the organization by member vote.

question.en-US: How can I become a member of Salon?

answer.en-US: Salon welcomes applications from experienced, ethical art collectors. After you submit an application online and pass an initial screening, our members will vote to affirm or deny your membership. If your application is successful, you will contribute funds to Salon by purchasing Salon units, which represent your ownership stake and voting rights in Salon’s collection.

question.en-US: How does Salon use blockchain?

answer.en-US: Salon members interact with blockchain-based smart contracts to login, vote, transfer units, and receive distributions (members receive distributions only in the event that they vote to wind down Salon—by default, any gains are reinvested back into Salon’s treasury to purchase more art). Blockchain technology is seamlessly integrated into our tech stack—you’ll forget you’re using it.

question.en-US: How long does it take to verify my application?

answer.en-US: Accreditation and verification of members will take between 5 – 7 business days. We will reach out to you during the verification process with any questions or concerns.

question.en-US: How big will Salon get?

answer.en-US: Salon membership is capped at 100 collectors.

question.en-US: Can a member cancel or re-delegate their voting rights?

answer.en-US: A member can cancel or re-delegate their voting rights at any time.

question.en-US: Are there any legal requirements to joining Salon?

answer.en-US: For compliance reasons, membership in Salon is limited to accredited investors.

question.en-US: How long does it take for contributions to be processed?

answer.en-US: After a potential member’s contributions have been pledged and their application has been submitted, Salon members will vote to affirm or deny a member’s application. Salon’s voting period is 4 days. If denied, the potential member is released from their obligation to contribute. If approved, the applicant must complete funding within 14 days.

question.en-US: How are voting rights determined?

answer.en-US: Voting rights are based on the total number of Salon units that each member holds. In other words, voting power is proportional to a member’s ownership stake in Salon.

question.en-US: How do members vote?

answer.en-US: Members receive email notifications when their votes are required on new proposals. Votes are cast within Salon’s app.

medium.en-US: Acrylic, color pencil and flashe on canvas over panel

description.en-US: This meticulous hard-edged grid painting by the Korean-Canadian artist Hanna Hur evokes the preciscion of Agnes Martin and the legacy of Korean Minimalism. The Los Angeles-based artist seeks spirituality through her meditative and repetition-based practice.

question.en-US: Do all members have to vote on every decision?

answer.en-US: Members are not required to vote on all matters. Salon’s routine decisions are made with a simple majority—that is, the majority of those voting at that time.

question.en-US: How do you exit Salon?

answer.en-US: If members wish to exit Salon, they may do so at market value at that time by selling their ownership stake to an existing member or an approved new member from our waitlist. Salon’s app facilitates the safe transfer of units from one party to another.

question.en-US: Can a member be forced out of Salon?

answer.en-US: Members of Salon may be required to leave the organization in the event of serious violations to Salon’s operating agreement. This process is detailed further in our operating agreement, including compensation entitled to by such members.

question.en-US: Does delegating rights to vote on purchase decisions impact a member's right to proceeds?

answer.en-US: No.

question.en-US: Under what circumstances will Salon wind down?

answer.en-US: A supermajority of member votes is required to dissolve the organization and liquidate assets. If a dissolution were to occur, a person appointed by the members through majority vote will handle the wind-down based on the terms set out in the operating agreement.

question.en-US: If there are expenses associated with operating Salon, who is responsible for them?

answer.en-US: Salon and its members are responsible for the costs and expenses related to Salon’s activities, operations, and maintenance. Because we have no fund manager or storage facility, our operating expenses are extremely low.

question.en-US: Who controls Salon’s bank account?

answer.en-US: Salon has an elected Finance Committee, which maintains access to Salon’s bank account and is responsible for facilitating all transactions voted on by Salon’s members, such as acquiring artworks. Our Finance Committee is limited to 5 members and is reelected annually.

question.en-US: What happens if I’m too busy to vote?

answer.en-US: A member can transfer or "delegate" their voting rights to another member of Salon by choosing a delegate in Salon’s app.

question.en-US: How will Salon evolve?

answer.en-US:
Salon will continue its growth and evolution into a thriving community of global collectors, with an ever-growing trove of contemporary art. One day, we hope to rival museum collections in breadth and scale. Members are currently at work on ideas related to the compensation of artists in our collection in the event of future sales, establishing targets for diversity and inclusion, and strategic brand partnerships.

Wherever the journey takes us, Salon’s future belongs to its members.

For questions or to learn more about joining Salon, please get in touch at hello@salondao.xyz

code.en-US: We are a distributed online community of collectors, artists, gallerists, and creatives. Our Internet-based institution is shaped through our collective tastes, access, and insights.

code2.en-US: Our personal collections include works by leading artists spanning identities, periods, mediums, and practices.

question.en-US: How is the price of a Salon unit determined?

answer.en-US: The price of Salon’s units are underpinned by the value of Salon’s treasury, which contains all assets in Salon’s bank account, digital wallet, and the appraised value of Salon’s artworks. Salon retains a service provider to perform regular appraisals for each work in Salon’s collection, allowing us to maintain an up-to-date treasury.

question.en-US: Will Salon eventually run out of funds?

answer.en-US: Salon is designed to exist in perpetuity, and will continue purchasing artworks until all contributed capital has been allocated. Members may elect to periodically re-up their investments to Salon throughout its lifespan.

question.en-US: How are artworks sold by Salon?

answer.en-US: In the event that Salon’s members choose to deaccession a work from the collection, Salon’s Finance Committee will take steps to sell or consign the work on behalf of Salon’s members. There are no restrictions on how the work is sold, whether at auction, on an art marketplace, or directly to a collector.

question.en-US: How will proceeds be distributed?

answer.en-US: In the event members vote to dissolve Salon or distribute proceeds from artwork sales, members will receive proceeds on a pro-rata basis based on the number of Salon units each member holds.

question.en-US: How long does it take to vote on artwork purchases?

answer.en-US: After a member makes a proposal in our app to purchase a specific work, members have the opportunity to cast votes for or against the acquisition for 4 days. If the proposal passes, Salon’s Financial Committee will take steps to purchase the artwork.

question.en-US: How do members choose artworks to purchase?

answer.en-US: Salon’s current investment focus centers on emerging and mid-career living artists. All Salon members can bring opportunities to acquire works through the primary and secondary markets, galleries, online marketplaces, or artists directly. Any acquisition opportunity can be brought to Salon members for a vote by creating a proposal in Salon’s app.

question.en-US: Will Salon recycle or reinvest proceeds?

answer.en-US: Yes. By default, Salon’s profits will be held in Salon’s treasury and available for reinvestment.

question.en-US: Can members discuss potential acquisitions with other members before making a proposal in the app?

answer.en-US: Yes. Salon has a vibrant Whatsapp and Slack workspace in which acquisitions are discussed and debated at length before members propose a formal vote.

whyCollect0long.en-US:
Crowner is one of the most promising mid-career abstract artists working today. It is nearly impossible to collect one of her works in the primary market today, due to overwhelming demand. 

She is known for canvases in which each color and form is comprised of a different piece of cloth, attached via stitches. Her works feature geometric compositions and solid fields of color—a revisit to the traditions of the hard-edge abstraction pioneered in the 1950s and ’60s. 

Evident in Crowner’s paintings is her deep knowledge and involvement with tile: much like mosaics are created from the interplay of several tiles, her abstract canvases are constructed with individual pieces of canvas, which fused together make a whole that is far more tactile and active than may be apparent in their initial calm, elegant appearance.

Personally, Crowner's work speaks to me on a spiritual and aesthetic level—her compositions are cool, soothing, and enticing. Collecting a work of this caliber in Salon's early days sets our organization on an exciting path, and establishes a high bar we can hold ourselves to time and time again.

artistMarket0long.en-US:
Crowner has shown at a number of key museums and institutions, including the Whitney Biennial, Museum of Modern Art New York, The Chinati Foundation in Marfa, Dallas Museum of Art, Museo de Arte De Zapopan, Flag Art Foundation, and Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art.

Crowner's work rarely comes up at auction—her galleries have been successful at placing her works with top collectors who do not flip works. Salon would enter a trusted circle, with a responsibility to continue this tradition of holding Crowner's work for the long term.

Last year, a work of similar scale and composition sold at Art Basel from Casey Caplan's booth for $160,000. The price we've been offered, $100,000, is competitive and fair, with strong upside potential in the future.

whyCollect0long.en-US:
Mika Tajima is a true "critic's artist," her work is regarded internationally by curators and institutional leaders for its sophistication, rigor, and research-based elements. 

This particular work is an exemplary example of Mika's recognizable Art d’Ameublement series, yet rare in its more muted color palette. Typically the artist uses brighter shades, but this work gives the appearance of serene moonlight.

Mika Tajima describes this series as, "Airborne paint particles condense on the inner surface of the transparent acrylic shells that comprise the Art d’Ameublement series. The capture of these aerated solids creates vivid color gradients on the recto of the painting while obscuring views into the depths of its interior. Art d’Ameublement refers to Erik Satie’s Furniture Music (Musique d’ameublement)—a series of infinitely repetitive compositions meant to be background music, or aural décor, for different occasions. Drawing on the psycho-geographic associations of isolation and the unfathomable, each large-scale painting is subtitled with an uninhabited geographic location."

The artist also describes her Art D'Ameublement series in this video from Simon Lee Gallery: https://vimeo.com/528831565

artistMarket0long.en-US:
2022 has been Mika Tajima's breakout year. She had four solo shows this year alone, at leading galleries Kayne Griffin, Pace Gallery, Taro Nasu, and at the Japanese cultural institution Dazaifu Tenmangu.

Her work has been exhibited at Centre Pompidou, SF MoMA, the Aspen Art Museum, Bass Museum, The Kitchen, The Swiss Institute of Contemporary Art, Seattle Art Museum, and the Seattle Museum.

Mika was one of a select group of artists to gain formal representation with Pace Gallery after its merger with Kayne Griffin earlier this year. Pace has introduced Mika's work to its high tier clientele, and her dealer noted that Mika Tajima's work is sought after by her most sophisticated collectors, who "do not follow trends in the market, and instead buy for quality." The quality of the work is undeniable, truly "perfect" in the sense that it is without visible flaws.

Tajima has a sparse auction record, with nothing sold this year—a testament to the quality of the collectors who buy her works.

proposal0long.en-US: I'm initiating a proposal to implement a referral program, to reward Salon members who meaningfully participate in our fundraising efforts by bringing in new members.

whyProposal0long.en-US: Salon’s mission is to build the world’s largest co-owned and managed art collection, becoming the pre-eminent Internet-based institution in the process.  To achieve our goals and fuel our community’s growth, we must regularly bring in new members and new capital. A referral reward structure provides a strong financial incentive to participate in Salon's growth, further aligning our members.

description.en-US: Alicja Kwade’s Be-Hide series is concerned with the interplay of "being" and "hiding." A found stone and its replica cast in aluminum sit across each side of a two-sided mirror. The stone and its counterpart overlap perfectly in reflection, yet uncannily. From one perspective, the mirrored glass may appear as a normal reflecting plane, bearing an unchallenged reflection of the object in its gaze. As the viewer changes perspectives, the mirror begins to deny its reflectivity and appears as a transparent–yet transformational–window through which a natural stone looks onto its shiny metal double. Moving around the piece, the glass may gradually conceal parts of one of the objects, but in return, it will always complete what's missing by revealing its exact complement in a different material. Kwade's work belongs in the collections of the Centre Pompidou, the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, the Hirshhorn Museum, the Yuz Museum, the Burger Collection, and more.

sellerContact.en-US: Erika Weiss, Senior Director at 303 Gallery, erika@303gallery.com

whyCollect0long.en-US:
At Salon's recent member monthly meeting, all members present expressed strong interest in collecting a work by Alicja Kwade, representing a valuable and exciting moment of alignment for Salon's collective taste.

Alicja Kwade’s Be-Hide series is concerned with the interplay of "being" and "hiding." A found stone and its replica cast in aluminum sit across each side of a two-sided mirror. The stone and its counterpart overlap perfectly in reflection, yet uncannily. 

From one perspective, the mirrored glass may appear as a normal reflecting plane, bearing an unchallenged reflection of the object in its gaze. As the viewer changes perspectives, the mirror begins to deny its reflectivity and appears as a transparent–yet transformational–window through which a natural stone looks onto its shiny metal double. 

Moving around the piece, the glass may gradually conceal parts of one of the objects, but in return, it will always complete what's missing by revealing its exact complement in a different material.

The conceptual and rigorous nature of Alicja Kwade's work complements Salon's existing collection, as well as providing an opportunity to acquire Salon's first sculptural work, a welcome addition.

We were also able to negotiate a generous 13% discount, rare for a work from a desirable series like this. We were told Be-Hide is Alicja's most in-demand series.

artistMarket0long.en-US:
According to Artsy data, Kwade's works at auction historically sell at 124% over estimate. This week, two lots by Kwade were included in a Sotheby's auction: 1 lot surpassed its high estimate of $120,000 to hammer at $165,000, and the second came close to its high estimate of $200,000 to hammer at $190,500 (surpassing its low estimate of $150,000). 

Kwade is seeing strong trajectory in the gallery scene, with a sold-out show at OMR in Mexico City last month, recent solo shows at Pace Gallery Seoul, Konig Gallery, and 303 Gallery, as well as an installation in Paris' Place Vendome during Paris+ last year, sponsored by the fair with support from French gallery Kamel Mennour.

proposal0long.en-US: We recently brought Salon's artwork insurance in-house under a centralized policy. With effective coverage in place, it's time to pass our hosting policy and begin shipping artworks to member homes.

whyProposal0long.en-US:
The hosting policy governs how members will display works from Salon’s collection in their residences, where they can be shared with friends, family, and community. Hosting keeps Salon’s operating costs manageable by negating the need for storage, in addition to providing an equitable framework for handling insurance fees, where hosts assume insurance costs in accordance with the overall value of the works they elect to take home.  

The attached policy (PDF) comes with the full endorsement of Salon's Financial Committee.

resourcesRequired0long.en-US:
Carrying out our hosting program requires financial and administrative resources. Annual insurance is paid upfront by Salon, but eventually reimbursed by members who elect to bring artworks home. 

Administrative hours will be bourn by Jordan Huelskamp, who will act as the hosting program's primary facilitator by arranging shipping, insurance scheduling, annual invoicing, and framing logistics with members.

images0upload.en-US: [{"type":"image/jpeg","name":"Janaina Tschäpe, Maiden Dawn, 2022.jpg","size":309022,"url":"https://upcdn.io/12a1xmBCtCfJ6zZeoHpAW2V"},{"type":"image/jpeg","name":"Janaina Tschäpe, Maiden Dawn, 2022 (Detail).jpg","size":607982,"url":"https://upcdn.io/12a1xmB5s2bssrtRjqgL7MW"}]

artworkMedium.en-US: Oil and oil stick on canvas

whyCollect0long.en-US:
Janaina Tschäpe is a mid-career Brazilian-German artist in her early 50s, who has received institutional recognition and critical acclaim throughout her career. Tschäpe's works incorporate themes of aquatic, plant, and human life to suggest dreamlike, abstract landscapes that blur perceptions of illusion and reality. Referencing interests in myth, morphology, and the mysteries of aquatic states, she has developed a distinctive language of abstraction in which organic forms are imbued with remarkable luminosity.

When evaluating her work at a recent Salon Member Monthly meeting, attendees unanimously vibed with Tschäpe’s works on a visual and instinctual level. I personally view "Maiden Dawn" in particular as a highly re-sellable piece, with more muted neutral tones that will go well in many homes. The size is also more forgiving than some of Tschäpe’s other, grander pieces which are difficult to find homes for. For these reasons I think this work is the best choice for Salon.

artistMarket0long.en-US:
I believe Tschäpe is strongly positioned amidst the cresting market interest in contemporary abstraction, and as an overlooked female artist, her prices are still attainable with potential to trend upward.

Tschäpe is represented by bicoastal Sean Kelly Gallery, the Brazilian powerhouse Fortes D'Aloia & Gabriel, and the Copenhagen-based Galleri Bo Bjerggaard, giving her strong exposure in international markets. Her recent show in Los Angeles, timed during Frieze Los Angeles, hints at Sean Kelly's desire to position Tschäpe at the foreground of their gallery's program. This show, and the momentum around the artist at this time, caused Tschäpe to be recognized as the 16th most-inquired on artist on Artsy in Q1 2023.

Tschäpe’s work is found in public collections including Centre Pompidou, Paris, France; Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofía, Madrid, Spain; Harvard Art Museum, Cambridge, Massachusetts; Museu de Arte Moderna do Rio de Janeiro, Brazil; Moderna Museet, Stockholm, Sweden; Thyssen-Bornemisza Art Contemporary, Vienna, Austria; and the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, New York, among others. She has completed public commissions in New York City; Miami Beach, Florida; São Paulo, Brazil; and Holbæk, Denmark.

She has had solo exhibitions at the Den Frie Center of Contemporary Art, Copenhagen, Denmark; the Sarasota Art Museum, Florida; the Musée L’Orangerie, Paris, France; the Museum of Contemporary Art Tucson, Arizona; Kasama Nichido Museum of Art, Kasama, Japan; the Irish Museum of Modern Art, Dublin, Ireland, and the Contemporary Museum of Art, St Louis.

The artist's large canvas works have rarely come up for auction, with one coming up in 2015 and selling for $81,250 (a 2012 work, this is also her auction record) and another coming up in 2018 and selling for $40,000 (though that example is a 2007 work). A small watercolor sold at a benefit auction this week for $26,000. An artist of her stage and caliber with few works at auction points to a less speculative market, and high-quality collectors that hold for the long term.

proposal0long.en-US: Ratify by vote Salon's "Core Curatorial Criteria," giving our community a framework to assess acquisition decisions through a set of objective evaluation criteria.

whyProposal0long.en-US:
Throughout the lifespan of our fund, members have grappled with how to balance subjective and objective criteria when assessing artwork purchase decisions, and ultimately, voting. 

We all have unique opinions on what art is beautiful and what art we like (i.e. "subjective" criteria). That is to be expected and celebrated. While subjective differences within our member community are rather straightforward, and addressed through Salon's democratic voting framework, our community has yet to align on a set of objective attributes we are looking for in all purchase decisions.

The Core Curatorial Criteria ("CCC") introduces a ten-point scoring system our members can use as a framework when discussing and evaluating artworks together. The ten point system identifies widely agreed-upon attributes that help predict an artwork's expected cultural + financial appreciation (i.e. "objective" criteria). 

Artworks do not necessarily need to meet a certain threshold* on the ten-point system, unless otherwise decided by members through a community vote—rather, the score exists as a tool for discussion and is used by members to inform their voting decisions. 

*For example, an artwork with a score of ten would be very likely to appreciate in value. An artwork with a score of zero would be a riskier purchase decision for the fund, lacking indications that the artwork would go up in value.

resourcesRequired0long.en-US: None, the Financial Committee has already drafted the Core Curatorial Criteria and no further work will be required.

whyCollect0long.en-US:
Oscar Murillo has developed a multifaceted and inventive art practice, which constantly probes questions of collectivity and shared culture, while being fundamentally connected to the affective qualities of different materials.

Murillo creates works with a social dimension, which exist at the border between performances and events. He has invited collaborators to participate in actions including walking through New York or travelling between UK cities carrying mateos (traditional papier-mâché figures made in Colombia), painting swathes of linen black in locations around the world, or holding a party for the cleaning staff of London’s Serpentine Galleries. Since 2013, for the durational project Frequencies, Murillo organised for over 100,000 school students to have blank canvas fixed to their desks, allowing them to freely mark, draw and write on them over a period of months. The project has so far amassed an archive of over 40,000 examples from around the world. These nuanced projects involve others as participants, as opposed to merely viewers, and point to a perpetual curiosity into complex issues of global social and economic relations, community, and spectatorship.

A quote below from a recent article in the Guardian from writer Tim Lewis:
"Oscar Murillo, 37, exploded on to the global art scene a decade ago, becoming known as “the 21st-century Basquiat”. Born in Colombia, he moved with his family to London when he was 10. He graduated from the Royal College of Art, and worked as a cleaner and a teacher until 2013 when one of his paintings, with an estimated value of $30,000, sold for $401,000 at auction in New York. In 2019, Murillo – whose work includes paintings, videos and room-sized installations – was one of four artists to be jointly awarded the Turner prize. He has new work showing as part of To Bend the Ear of the Outer World, a show examining contemporary abstract painting at Gagosian, London."

I believe Salon should purchase a work by Oscar Murillo because he is one of the contemporary artists today who are really holding up a mirror to society, he challenges the conventional ideas of painting and at 37 he has already reached unbelievable success primarily by the support of the Rubells. 

The artist has appeared in major international shows such as the 2015 Venice Biennale, “The Forever Now: Contemporary Painting in an Atemporal World,” at New York’s Museum of Modern Art in 2014, as well as, this year, the Marrakech Biennale and the Biennale of Sydney.
